# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: merge-sort-algorithm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] A **comparison sort** is a type of sorting algorithm that only reads the list elements through a single abstract comparison operation (often a "less than or equal to" operator or a three-way comparison) that determines which of two elements should occur first in the final sorted list.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] It is possible that both *a* ≤ *b* and *b* ≤ *a* with *a* ≠ *b*; in this case either may come first in the sorted list.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] In a stable sort, the input order determines the sorted order in this case.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Comparison sorts studied in the literature are "comparison-based".
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Elements *a* and *b* can be swapped or otherwise re-arranged by the algorithm only when the order between these elements has been established based on the outcomes of prior comparisons.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This is the case when the order between *a* and *b* can be derived via the transitive closure of these prior comparison outcomes.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] For comparison-based sorts, the decision to execute basic operations other than comparisons is based on the outcome of comparisons.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Hence in a time analysis, the number of executed comparisons is used to determine upper bound estimates for the number of executed basic operations such as swaps or assignments.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] A metaphor for thinking about comparison sorts is that someone has a set of unlabelled weights and a balance scale.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Their goal is to line up the weights in order by their weight without any information except that obtained by placing two weights on the scale and seeing which one is heavier (or if they weigh the same).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] There are fundamental limits on the performance of comparison sorts.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] A comparison sort must have an average-case lower bound of Ω(*n* log *n*) comparison operations, which is known as linearithmic time.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This is a consequence of the limited information available through comparisons alone — or, to put it differently, of the vague algebraic structure of totally ordered sets.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] In this sense, mergesort, heapsort, and introsort are asymptotically optimal in terms of the number of comparisons they must perform, although this metric neglects other operations.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Non-comparison sorts (such as the examples discussed below) can achieve O(*n*) performance by using operations other than comparisons, allowing them to sidestep this lower bound (assuming elements are constant-sized).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Comparison sorts may run faster on some lists; many adaptive sorts such as insertion sort run in O(*n*) time on an already-sorted or nearly-sorted list.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The Ω(*n* log *n*) lower bound applies only to the case in which the input list can be in any possible order.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Despite these limitations, comparison sorts offer the notable practical advantage that control over the comparison function allows sorting of many different datatypes and fine control over how the list is sorted.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Comparison sorts generally adapt more easily to complex orders such as the order of floating-point numbers.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Additionally, once a comparison function is written, any comparison sort can be used without modification; non-comparison sorts typically require specialized versions for each datatype.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This flexibility, together with the efficiency of the above comparison sorting algorithms on modern computers, has led to widespread preference for comparison sorts in most practical work.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Some sorting problems admit a strictly faster solution than the Ω(*n* log *n*) bound for comparison sorting by using non-comparison sorts; an example is integer sorting, where all keys are integers.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] When the keys form a small (compared to n) range, counting sort is an example algorithm that runs in linear time.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Other integer sorting algorithms, such as radix sort, are not asymptotically faster than comparison sorting, but can be faster in practice.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The problem of sorting pairs of numbers by their sum is not subject to the Ω(*n*² log *n*) bound either (the square resulting from the pairing up); the best known algorithm still takes O(*n*² log *n*) time, but only O(*n*²) comparisons.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The number of comparisons that a comparison sort algorithm requires increases in proportion to $n\log(n)$ , where n is the number of elements to sort.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Given a list of distinct numbers (we can assume this because this is a worst-case analysis), there are n factorial permutations exactly one of which is the list in sorted order.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The sort algorithm must gain enough information from the comparisons to identify the correct permutation.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] If the algorithm always completes after at most $f(n)$ steps, it cannot distinguish more than $2^{f(n)}$ cases because the keys are distinct and each comparison has only two possible outcomes.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This provides the lower-bound part of the claim.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] A more precise bound can be given via Stirling's approximation.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] An upper bound of the same form, with the same leading term as the bound obtained from Stirling's approximation, follows from the existence of the algorithms that attain this bound in the worst case, like merge sort.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The above argument provides an *absolute*, rather than only asymptotic lower bound on the number of comparisons, namely $\left\lceil \log _{2}(n!)\right\rceil$ comparisons.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This lower bound is fairly good (it can be approached within a linear tolerance by a simple merge sort), but it is known to be inexact.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] For example, $\left\lceil \log _{2}(13!)\right\rceil =33$ , but the minimal number of comparisons to sort 13 elements has been proved to be 34.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Determining the *exact* number of comparisons needed to sort a given number of entries is a computationally hard problem even for small *n*, and no simple formula for the solution is known.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] For some of the few concrete values that have been computed, see OEIS: A036604.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] A similar bound applies to the average number of comparisons.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] it is impossible to determine which order the input is in with fewer than log2(*n*!) comparisons on average.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This can be most easily seen using concepts from information theory.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The Shannon entropy of such a random permutation is log2(*n*!) bits.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Since a comparison can give only two results, the maximum amount of information it provides is 1 bit.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Therefore, after *k* comparisons the remaining entropy of the permutation, given the results of those comparisons, is at least log2(*n*!) − *k* bits on average.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] To perform the sort, complete information is needed, so the remaining entropy must be 0.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] It follows that *k* must be at least log2(*n*!) on average.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The lower bound derived via information theory is phrased as 'information-theoretic lower bound'.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The information-theoretic lower bound is correct, but may be far from the strongest possible lower bound.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] For example, the information-theoretic lower bound of selection is $\left\lceil \log _{2}(n)\right\rceil$ whereas $n-1$ comparisons are needed by an adversarial argument.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The interplay between information-theoretic lower bound and the true lower bound are much like a real-valued function lower-bounding an integer function.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] However, this is not exactly correct when the average case is considered.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] To unearth what happens while analyzing the average case, the key is that what does 'average' refer to?
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] With some knowledge of information theory, the information-theoretic lower bound averages over the set of all permutations as a whole.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] But any computer algorithms (under what are believed currently) must treat each permutation as an individual instance of the problem.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Hence, the average lower bound we're searching for is averaged over all individual cases.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] To search for the lower bound relating to the non-achievability of computers, we adopt the Decision tree model.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Let's rephrase a bit of what our objective is.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] In the Decision tree model, the lower bound to be shown is the lower bound of the average length of root-to-leaf paths of an $n!$ -leaf binary tree (in which each leaf corresponds to a permutation).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The minimum average length of a binary tree with a given number of leaves is achieved by a balanced full binary tree, because any other binary tree can have its path length reduced by moving a pair of leaves to a higher position.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] For example, for *n* = 3, the information-theoretic lower bound for the average case is approximately 2.58, while the average lower bound derived via Decision tree model is 8/3, approximately 2.67.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] In the case that multiple items may have the same key, there is no obvious statistical interpretation for the term "average case", so an argument like the above cannot be applied without making specific assumptions about the distribution of keys.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Can easy compute for real algorithm sorted-list-merging (array are sorted n-blocks with size 1, merge to 1–1 to 2, merge 2–2 to 4...).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] If a list is already close to sorted, according to some measure of sortedness, the number of comparisons required to sort it can be smaller.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] An adaptive sort takes advantage of this "presortedness" and runs more quickly on nearly-sorted inputs, often while still maintaining an $O(n\log n)$ worst case time bound.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] An example is adaptive heap sort, a sorting algorithm based on Cartesian trees.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/comparison-sort] It takes time $O(n\log k)$ , where k is the average, over all values x in the sequence, of the number of times the sequence jumps from below x to above x or vice versa.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In computer science, **divide and conquer** is an algorithm design paradigm.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] A divide-and-conquer algorithm recursively breaks down a problem into two or more sub-problems of the same or related type, until these become simple enough to be solved directly.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The solutions to the sub-problems are then combined to give a solution to the original problem.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Designing efficient divide-and-conquer algorithms can be difficult.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] As in mathematical induction, it is often necessary to generalize the problem to make it amenable to a recursive solution.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The correctness of a divide-and-conquer algorithm is usually proved by mathematical induction, and its computational cost is often determined by solving recurrence relations.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The divide-and-conquer paradigm is often used to find an optimal solution of a problem.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Its basic idea is to decompose a given problem into two or more similar, but simpler, subproblems, to solve them in turn, and to compose their solutions to solve the given problem.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Problems of sufficient simplicity are solved directly.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, to sort a given list of *n* natural numbers, split it into two lists of about *n*/2 numbers each, sort each of them in turn, and interleave both results appropriately to obtain the sorted version of the given list (see the picture).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This approach is known as the merge sort algorithm.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The name "divide and conquer" is sometimes applied to algorithms that reduce each problem to only one sub-problem, such as the binary search algorithm for finding a record in a sorted list (or its analogue in numerical computing, the bisection algorithm for root finding).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] These algorithms can be implemented more efficiently than general divide-and-conquer algorithms; in particular, if they use tail recursion, they can be converted into simple loops.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Under this broad definition, however, every algorithm that uses recursion or loops could be regarded as a "divide-and-conquer algorithm".
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Therefore, some authors consider that the name "divide and conquer" should be used only when each problem may generate two or more subproblems.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The name **decrease and conquer** has been proposed instead for the single-subproblem class.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Early examples of these algorithms are primarily decrease and conquer – the original problem is successively broken down into *single* subproblems, and indeed can be solved iteratively.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Binary search, a decrease-and-conquer algorithm where the subproblems are of roughly half the original size, has a long history.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] While a clear description of the algorithm on computers appeared in 1946 in an article by John Mauchly, the idea of using a sorted list of items to facilitate searching dates back at least as far as Babylonia in 200 BC.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Another ancient decrease-and-conquer algorithm is the Euclidean algorithm to compute the greatest common divisor of two numbers by reducing the numbers to smaller and smaller equivalent subproblems, which dates to several centuries BC.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] An early two-subproblem D&C algorithm that was specifically developed for computers and properly analyzed is the merge sort algorithm, invented by John von Neumann in 1945.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Another notable example is the algorithm invented by Anatolii A.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Karatsuba in 1960 that could multiply two *n*-digit numbers in $O(n^{\log _{2}3})$ operations (in Big O notation).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This algorithm disproved Andrey Kolmogorov's 1956 conjecture that $\Omega (n^{2})$ operations would be required for that task.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This is related to a radix sort, described for punch-card sorting machines as early as 1929.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide and conquer is a powerful tool for solving conceptually difficult problems: all it requires is a way of breaking the problem into sub-problems, of solving the trivial cases, and of combining sub-problems to the original problem.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Similarly, decrease and conquer only requires reducing the problem to a single smaller problem, such as the classic Tower of Hanoi puzzle, which reduces moving a tower of height n to move a tower of height $n-1$ .
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The divide-and-conquer paradigm often helps in the discovery of efficient algorithms.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] It was the key, for example, to Karatsuba's fast multiplication method, the quicksort and mergesort algorithms, the Strassen algorithm for matrix multiplication, and fast Fourier transforms.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In all these examples, the D&C approach led to an improvement in the asymptotic cost of the solution.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For other types of divide-and-conquer approaches, running times can also be generalized.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] If, instead, the work of splitting the problem and combining the partial solutions take $cn^{2}$ time, and there are 2 subproblems where each has size ${\frac {n}{2}}$ , then the running time of the divide-and-conquer algorithm is bounded by $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms are naturally adapted for execution in multi-processor machines, especially shared-memory systems where the communication of data between processors does not need to be planned in advance because distinct sub-problems can be executed on different processors.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms naturally tend to make efficient use of memory caches.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The reason is that once a sub-problem is small enough, it and all its sub-problems can, in principle, be solved within the cache, without accessing the slower main memory.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] An algorithm designed to exploit the cache in this way is called *cache-oblivious*, because it does not contain the cache size as an explicit parameter.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Moreover, D&C algorithms can be designed for important algorithms (e.g., sorting, FFTs, and matrix multiplication) to be *optimal* cache-oblivious algorithms–they use the cache in a probably optimal way, in an asymptotic sense, regardless of the cache size.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The same advantage exists with regards to other hierarchical storage systems, such as NUMA or virtual memory, as well as for multiple levels of cache: once a sub-problem is small enough, it can be solved within a given level of the hierarchy, without accessing the higher (slower) levels.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In computations with rounded arithmetic, e.g. with floating-point numbers, a divide-and-conquer algorithm may yield more accurate results than a superficially equivalent iterative method.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, one can add *N* numbers either by a simple loop that adds each datum to a single variable, or by a D&C algorithm called pairwise summation that breaks the data set into two halves, recursively computes the sum of each half, and then adds the two sums.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] While the second method performs the same number of additions as the first and pays the overhead of the recursive calls, it is usually more accurate.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms are naturally implemented as recursive procedures.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In that case, the partial sub-problems leading to the one currently being solved are automatically stored in the procedure call stack.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] A recursive function is a function that calls itself within its definition.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms can also be implemented by a non-recursive program that stores the partial sub-problems in some explicit data structure, such as a stack, queue, or priority queue.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This approach allows more freedom in the choice of the sub-problem that is to be solved next, a feature that is important in some applications — e.g. in breadth-first recursion and the branch-and-bound method for function optimization.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This approach is also the standard solution in programming languages that do not provide support for recursive procedures.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In recursive implementations of D&C algorithms, one must make sure that there is sufficient memory allocated for the recursion stack, otherwise, the execution may fail because of stack overflow.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] D&C algorithms that are time-efficient often have relatively small recursion depth.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, the quicksort algorithm can be implemented so that it never requires more than $\log _{2}n$ nested recursive calls to sort n items.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Stack overflow can be difficult to prevent when using recursive procedures, since many compilers treat the recursion stack as a contiguous block of memory, and some reserve a fixed amount of space for it.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In addition, compilers may store more information on the recursion stack than is strictly required, including the return address, unchanged parameters, and the procedure’s local variables.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] As a result, the likelihood of stack overflow may be reduced by limiting the number of parameters and local variables in the recursive procedure, or by replacing recursion with an explicit stack data structure.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In any recursive algorithm, there is considerable freedom in the choice of the *base cases*, the small subproblems that are solved directly in order to terminate the recursion.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Choosing the smallest or simplest possible base cases is more elegant and usually leads to simpler programs, because there are fewer cases to consider and they are easier to solve.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, a Fast Fourier Transform algorithm could stop the recursion when the input is a single sample, and the quicksort list-sorting algorithm could stop when the input is the empty list; in both examples, there is only one base case to consider, and it requires no processing.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] On the other hand, efficiency often improves if the recursion is stopped at relatively large base cases, and these are solved non-recursively, resulting in a hybrid algorithm.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This strategy avoids the overhead of recursive calls that do little or no work and may also allow the use of specialized non-recursive algorithms that, for those base cases, are more efficient than explicit recursion.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] A general procedure for a simple hybrid recursive algorithm is *short-circuiting the base case*, also known as *arm's-length recursion*.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In this case, whether the next step will result in the base case is checked before the function call, avoiding an unnecessary function call.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, in a tree, rather than recursing to a child node and then checking whether it is null, checking null before recursing avoids half the function calls in some algorithms on binary trees.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Since a D&C algorithm eventually reduces each problem or sub-problem instance to a large number of base instances, these often dominate the overall cost of the algorithm, especially when the splitting/joining overhead is low.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Note that these considerations do not depend on whether recursion is implemented by the compiler or by an explicit stack.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Thus, for example, many library implementations of quicksort will switch to a simple loop-based insertion sort (or similar) algorithm once the number of items to be sorted is sufficiently small.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Note that, if the empty list were the only base case, sorting a list with n entries would entail maximally n quicksort calls that would do nothing but return immediately.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Increasing the base cases to lists of size 2 or less will eliminate most of those do-nothing calls, and more generally a base case larger than 2 is typically used to reduce the fraction of time spent in function-call overhead or stack manipulation.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, this approach is used in some efficient FFT implementations, where the base cases are unrolled implementations of divide-and-conquer FFT algorithms for a set of fixed sizes.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Source-code generation methods may be used to produce the large number of separate base cases desirable to implement this strategy efficiently.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The generalized version of this idea is known as recursion "unrolling" or "coarsening", and various techniques have been proposed for automating the procedure of enlarging the base case.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For some problems, the branched recursion may end up evaluating the same sub-problem many times over.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In such cases it may be worth identifying and saving the solutions to these overlapping subproblems, a technique which is commonly known as memoization.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Followed to the limit, it leads to bottom-up divide-and-conquer algorithms such as dynamic programming.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] External sorting algorithms generally fall into two types, distribution sorting, which resembles quicksort, and external merge sort, which resembles merge sort.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] External merge sort typically uses a hybrid sort-merge strategy.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] In the sorting phase, chunks of data small enough to fit in main memory are read, sorted, and written out to a temporary file.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] In the merge phase, the sorted subfiles are combined into a single larger file.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] External sorting algorithms can be analyzed in the external memory model.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] In this model, a cache or internal memory of size M and an unbounded external memory are divided into blocks of size B, and the running time of an algorithm is determined by the number of memory transfers between internal and external memory.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] Like their cache-oblivious counterparts, asymptotically optimal external sorting algorithms achieve a running time (in Big O notation) of $O\left({\tfrac {N}{B}}\log _{\tfrac {M}{B}}{\tfrac {N}{B}}\right)$ .
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] One example of external sorting is the external merge sort algorithm, which uses a K-way merge algorithm.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] It sorts chunks that each fit in RAM, then merges the sorted chunks together.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] The algorithm first sorts M items at a time and puts the sorted lists back into external memory.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] It does a ${\tfrac {M}{B}}$ -way merge on those sorted lists, recursing if there is not enough main memory to merge efficiently in one pass.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] During a merge pass, B elements from each sorted list are in internal memory, and the minimum is repeatedly outputted.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] Repeat steps 1 and 2 until all of the data is in sorted 100 MB chunks (there are 900MB / 100MB = 9 chunks), which now need to be merged into one single output file.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] Read the first 10 MB (= 100MB / (9 chunks + 1)) of each sorted chunk into input buffers in main memory and allocate the remaining 10 MB for an output buffer.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] Perform a 9-way merge and store the result in the output buffer.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] Whenever the output buffer fills, write it to the final sorted file and empty it.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] Whenever any of the 9 input buffers empties, fill it with the next 10 MB of its associated 100 MB sorted chunk until no more data from the chunk is available.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] The merge pass is key to making external merge sort work externally.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] The merge algorithm only makes one pass through each chunk, so chunks do not have to be loaded all at once; rather, sequential parts of the chunk are loaded as needed.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] And as long as the blocks read are relatively large (like the 10 MB in this example), the reads can be relatively efficient even on media with low random-read performance, like hard drives.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] Historically, instead of a sort, sometimes a replacement-selection algorithm was used to perform the initial distribution, to produce on average half as many output chunks of double the length.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] The previous example is a two-pass sort: first sort, then merge.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] The sort ends with a single *k*-way merge, rather than a series of two-way merge passes as in a typical in-memory merge sort.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] This is because each merge pass reads and writes *every value* from and to disk, so reducing the number of passes more than compensates for the additional cost of a *k*-way merge.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] The limitation to single-pass merging is that as the number of chunks increases, memory will be divided into more buffers, so each buffer is smaller.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] Eventually, the reads become so small that more time is spent on disk seeks than data transfer.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] A typical magnetic hard disk drive might have a 10 ms access time and 100 MB/s data transfer rate, so each seek takes as much time as transferring 1 MB of data.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] Thus, for sorting, say, 50 GB in 100 MB of RAM, using a single 500-way merge pass isn't efficient: we can only read 100 MB / 501 ≈ 200 KB from each chunk at once, so 5/6 of the disk's time is spent seeking.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] Using two merge passes solves the problem.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] Run a first merge pass combining 25×100 MB chunks at a time, resulting in 20×2.5 GB sorted chunks.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] Although this requires an additional pass over the data, each read is now 4 MB long, so only 1/5 of the disk's time is spent seeking.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] The improvement in data transfer efficiency during the merge passes (16.6% to 80% is almost a 5× improvement) more than makes up for the doubled number of merge passes.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] Variations include using an intermediate medium like solid-state disk for some stages; the fast temporary storage needn't be big enough to hold the whole dataset, just substantially larger than available main memory.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] Repeating the example above with 1 GB of temporary SSD storage, the first pass could merge 10×100 MB sorted chunks read from that temporary space to write 50x1 GB sorted chunks to HDD.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] The high bandwidth and random-read throughput of SSDs help speed the first pass, and the HDD reads for the second pass can then be 2 MB, large enough that seeks will not take up most of the read time.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] SSDs can also be used as read buffers in a merge phase, allowing fewer larger reads (20MB reads in this example) from HDD storage.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] Given the lower cost of SSD capacity relative to RAM, SSDs can be an economical tool for sorting large inputs with very limited memory.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] Like in-memory sorts, efficient external sorts require O(*n* log *n*) time: exponentially growing datasets require linearly increasing numbers of passes that each take O(n) time.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] Under reasonable assumptions at least 500 GB of data stored on a hard drive can be sorted using 1 GB of main memory before a third pass becomes advantageous, and many times that much data can be sorted before a fourth pass becomes useful.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] Doubling memory dedicated to sorting halves the number of chunks *and* the number of reads per chunk, reducing the number of seeks required by about three-quarters.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] The ratio of RAM to disk storage on servers often makes it convenient to do huge sorts on a cluster of machines rather than on one machine with multiple passes.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] Media with high random-read performance like solid-state drives (SSDs) also increase the amount that can be sorted before additional passes improve performance.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] External distribution sort is analogous to quicksort.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] The algorithm finds approximately ${\tfrac {M}{B}}$ pivots and uses them to divide the N elements into approximately equally sized subarrays, each of whose elements are all smaller than the next, and then recurse until the sizes of the subarrays are less than the block size.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] When the subarrays are less than the block size, sorting can be done quickly because all reads and writes are done in the cache, and in the external memory model requires $O(1)$ operations.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] However, finding exactly ${\tfrac {M}{B}}$ pivots would not be fast enough to make the external distribution sort asymptotically optimal.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] To find these pivots, the algorithm splits the N input elements into ${\tfrac {N}{M}}$ chunks, and takes every ${\sqrt {\tfrac {M}{16B}}}$ elements, and recursively uses the median of medians algorithm to find ${\sqrt {\tfrac {M}{B}}}$ pivots.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] There is a duality, or fundamental similarity, between merge- and distribution-based algorithms.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/external-sorting] The Sort Benchmark, created by computer scientist Jim Gray, compares external sorting algorithms implemented using finely tuned hardware and software.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] The merge algorithm plays a critical role in the merge sort algorithm, a comparison-based sorting algorithm.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] Repeatedly merge sublists to create a new sorted sublist until the single list contains all elements.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] The merge algorithm is used repeatedly in the merge sort algorithm.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] An example merge sort is given in the illustration.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] It starts with an unsorted array of 7 integers.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] The array is divided into 7 partitions; each partition contains 1 element and is sorted.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] The sorted partitions are then merged to produce larger, sorted, partitions, until 1 partition, the sorted array, is left.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] Merging two sorted lists into one can be done in linear time and linear or constant space (depending on the data access model).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] The following pseudocode demonstrates an algorithm that merges input lists (either linked lists or arrays) A and B into a new list C.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] The function head yields the first element of a list; "dropping" an element means removing it from its list, typically by incrementing a pointer or index.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] When the inputs are linked lists, this algorithm can be implemented to use only a constant amount of working space; the pointers in the lists' nodes can be reused for bookkeeping and for constructing the final merged list.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] In the merge sort algorithm, this subroutine is typically used to merge two sub-arrays A[lo..mid], A[mid+1..hi] of a single array A.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] This can be done by copying the sub-arrays into a temporary array, then applying the merge algorithm above.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] The allocation of a temporary array can be avoided, but at the expense of speed and programming ease.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] Various in-place merge algorithms have been devised, sometimes sacrificing the linear-time bound to produce an *O*(*n* log *n*) algorithm; see Merge sort § Variants for discussion.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] k-way merging generalizes binary merging to an arbitrary number k of sorted input lists.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] Applications of k-way merging arise in various sorting algorithms, including patience sorting and an external sorting algorithm that divides its input into *k* = ⁠1/*M*⁠ − 1 blocks that fit in memory, sorts these one by one, then merges these blocks.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] Several solutions to this problem exist.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] In the worst case, this algorithm performs (*k*−1)(*n*−⁠*k*/2⁠) element comparisons to perform its work if there are a total of n elements in the lists.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] Searching for the next smallest element to be output (find-min) and restoring heap order can now be done in *O*(log *k*) time (more specifically, 2⌊log *k*⌋ comparisons), and the full problem can be solved in *O*(*n* log *k*) time (approximately 2*n*⌊log *k*⌋ comparisons).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] When the input lists to this algorithm are ordered by length, shortest first, it requires fewer than *n*⌈log *k*⌉ comparisons, i.e., less than half the number used by the heap-based algorithm; in practice, it may be about as fast or slow as the heap-based algorithm.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] A parallel version of the binary merge algorithm can serve as a building block of a parallel merge sort.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] The following pseudocode demonstrates this algorithm in a parallel divide-and-conquer style (adapted from Cormen *et al.*).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] It operates on two sorted arrays A and B and writes the sorted output to array C.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] The notation A[i...j] denotes the part of A from index i through j, exclusive.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] The algorithm operates by splitting either A or B, whichever is larger, into (nearly) equal halves.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] It then splits the other array into a part with values smaller than the midpoint of the first, and a part with larger or equal values.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] (The binary search subroutine returns the index in B where *A*[*r*] would be, if it were in B; that this always a number between k and ℓ.) Finally, each pair of halves is merged recursively, and since the recursive calls are independent of each other, they can be done in parallel.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] The work performed by the algorithm for two arrays holding a total of n elements, i.e., the running time of a serial version of it, is *O*(*n*).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] This is optimal since n elements need to be copied into C.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] To calculate the span of the algorithm, it is necessary to derive a Recurrence relation.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] Since the two recursive calls of *merge* are in parallel, only the costlier of the two calls needs to be considered.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] In the worst case, the maximum number of elements in one of the recursive calls is at most ${\textstyle {\frac {3}{4}}n}$ since the array with more elements is perfectly split in half.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] The solution is $T_{\infty }^{\text{merge}}(n)=\Theta \left(\log(n)^{2}\right)$ , meaning that it takes that much time on an ideal machine with an unbounded number of processors.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] There are also algorithms that introduce parallelism within a single instance of merging of two sorted lists.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] These can be used in field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs), specialized sorting circuits, as well as in modern processors with single-instruction multiple-data (SIMD) instructions.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] Existing parallel algorithms are based on modifications of the merge part of either the bitonic sorter or odd-even mergesort.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] In 2018, Saitoh M. et al. introduced MMS for FPGAs, which focused on removing a multi-cycle feedback datapath that prevented efficient pipelining in hardware.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] Also in 2018, Papaphilippou P. et al. introduced FLiMS that improved the hardware utilization and performance by only requiring $\log _{2}(P)+1$ pipeline stages of *P/2* compare-and-swap units to merge with a parallelism of *P* elements per FPGA cycle.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] Some computer languages provide built-in or library support for merging sorted collections.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] The C++'s Standard Template Library has the function std::merge, which merges two sorted ranges of iterators, and std::inplace_merge, which merges two consecutive sorted ranges *in-place*.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] In addition, the std::list (linked list) class has its own merge method which merges another list into itself.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] The type of the elements merged must support the less-than (<) operator, or it must be provided with a custom comparator.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] C++17 allows for differing execution policies, namely sequential, parallel, and parallel-unsequenced.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-algorithm] Python's standard library (since 2.6) also has a merge function in the heapq module, that takes multiple sorted iterables, and merges them into a single iterator.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Repeatedly merge sublists to produce new sorted sublists until there is only one sublist remaining.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Merge sort is efficient because merging and sorting two sublists can be performed in linear time, provided that the sublists are already sorted.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Example C-like code using indices for top-down merge sort algorithm that recursively splits the list into sublists (called *runs* in this example) until sublist size is 1, then merges those sublists to produce a sorted list.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] The copy back step is avoided with alternating the direction of the merge with each level of recursion (except for an initial one-time copy, that can be avoided too).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] As a simple example, consider an array with two elements.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] The elements are copied to `b`, then merged back to `a`.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] If there are four elements, when the bottom of the recursion level is reached, single element runs from `a` are merged to `b`, and then at the next higher level of recursion, those two-element runs are merged to `a`.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] This pattern continues with each level of recursion.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Sorting the entire array is accomplished by topDownMergeSort(a, b, a.length).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Pseudocode for top-down merge sort algorithm which recursively divides the input list into smaller sublists until the sublists are trivially sorted, and then merges the sublists while returning up the call chain.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] In this example, the merge function merges the left and right sublists.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Pseudocode for bottom-up merge sort algorithm which uses a small fixed size array of references to nodes, where `array[i]` is either a reference to a list of size 2*i* or *nil*.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] *node* is a reference or pointer to a node.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] The `merge()` function would be similar to the one shown in the top-down merge lists example, it merges two already sorted lists, and handles empty lists.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] In this case, `merge()` would use *node* for its input parameters and return value.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Haskell-like pseudocode, showing how merge sort can be implemented in such a language using constructs and ideas from functional programming.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] In sorting *n* objects, merge sort has an average and worst-case performance of O(*n* log *n*) comparisons.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] The closed form follows from the master theorem for divide-and-conquer recurrences.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] The number of comparisons made by merge sort in the worst case is given by the sorting numbers.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] These numbers are equal to or slightly smaller than (*n* ⌈lg *n*⌉ − 2⌈lg *n*⌉ + 1), which is between (*n* lg *n* − *n* + 1) and (*n* lg *n* + *n* + O(lg *n*)).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Merge sort's best case takes about half as many iterations as its worst case.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] In the *worst* case, merge sort uses approximately 39% fewer comparisons than quicksort does in its *average* case, and in terms of moves, merge sort's worst case complexity is O(*n* log *n*) - the same complexity as quicksort's best case.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Merge sort is more efficient than quicksort for some types of lists if the data to be sorted can only be efficiently accessed sequentially, and is thus popular in languages such as Lisp, where sequentially accessed data structures are very common.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Unlike some (efficient) implementations of quicksort, merge sort is a stable sort.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Merge sort's most common implementation does not sort in place; therefore, the memory size of the input must be allocated for the sorted output to be stored in (see below for variations that need only *n*/2 extra spaces).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] A natural merge sort is similar to a bottom-up merge sort except that any naturally occurring runs (sorted sequences) in the input are exploited.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Both monotonic and bitonic (alternating up/down) runs may be exploited, with lists (or equivalently tapes or files) being convenient data structures (used as FIFO queues or LIFO stacks).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] In the bottom-up merge sort, the starting point assumes each run is one item long.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] In practice, random input data will have many short runs that just happen to be sorted.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] In the typical case, the natural merge sort may not need as many passes because there are fewer runs to merge.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] In the best case, the input is already sorted (i.e., is one run), so the natural merge sort need only make one pass through the data.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] In many practical cases, long natural runs are present, and for that reason natural merge sort is exploited as the key component of Timsort.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Formally, the natural merge sort is said to be Runs-optimal, where ${\mathtt {Runs}}(L)$ is the number of runs in L , minus one.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Tournament replacement selection sorts are used to gather the initial runs for external sorting algorithms.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Instead of merging two blocks at a time, a ping-pong merge merges four blocks at a time.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] The four sorted blocks are merged simultaneously to auxiliary space into two sorted blocks, then the two sorted blocks are merged back to main memory.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Doing so omits the copy operation and reduces the total number of moves by half.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] An early public domain implementation of a four-at-once merge was by WikiSort in 2014, the method was later that year described as an optimization for patience sorting and named a ping-pong merge.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Quadsort implemented the method in 2020 and named it a quad merge.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] One drawback of merge sort, when implemented on arrays, is its *O*(*n*) working memory requirement.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] An external merge sort is practical to run using disk or tape drives when the data to be sorted is too large to fit into memory.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] External sorting explains how merge sort is implemented with disk drives.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] A typical tape drive sort uses four tape drives.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] All I/O is sequential (except for rewinds at the end of each pass).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] A minimal implementation can get by with just two record buffers and a few program variables.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Naming the four tape drives as A, B, C, D, with the original data on A, and using only two record buffers, the algorithm is similar to the bottom-up implementation, using pairs of tape drives instead of arrays in memory.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Merge two-record sublists from C and D into four-record sublists; writing these alternately to A and B.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Repeat until you have one list containing all the data, sorted—in log2(*n*) passes.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Instead of starting with very short runs, usually a hybrid algorithm is used, where the initial pass will read many records into memory, do an internal sort to create a long run, and then distribute those long runs onto the output set.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] For example, an internal sort of 1024 records will save nine passes.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] The internal sort is often large because it has such a benefit.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] In fact, there are techniques that can make the initial runs longer than the available internal memory.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] One of them, the Knuth's 'snowplow' (based on a binary min-heap), generates runs twice as long (on average) as a size of memory used.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] With some overhead, the above algorithm can be modified to use three tapes.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] *O*(*n* log *n*) running time can also be achieved using two queues, or a stack and a queue, or three stacks.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] In the other direction, using *k* > two tapes (and *O*(*k*) items in memory), we can reduce the number of tape operations in *O*(log *k*) times by using a k/2-way merge.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] A more sophisticated merge sort that optimizes tape (and disk) drive usage is the polyphase merge sort.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] On modern computers, locality of reference can be of paramount importance in software optimization, because multilevel memory hierarchies are used.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Cache-aware versions of the merge sort algorithm, whose operations have been specifically chosen to minimize the movement of pages in and out of a machine's memory cache, have been proposed.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] For example, the **tiled merge sort** algorithm stops partitioning subarrays when subarrays of size S are reached, where S is the number of data items fitting into a CPU's cache.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Each of these subarrays is sorted with an in-place sorting algorithm such as insertion sort, to discourage memory swaps, and normal merge sort is then completed in the standard recursive fashion.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] This algorithm has demonstrated better performance on machines that benefit from cache optimization.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Merge sort parallelizes well due to the use of the divide-and-conquer method.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Several different parallel variants of the algorithm have been developed over the years.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Some parallel merge sort algorithms are strongly related to the sequential top-down merge algorithm while others have a different general structure and use the K-way merge method.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] The sequential merge sort procedure can be described in two phases, the divide phase and the merge phase.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] The first consists of many recursive calls that repeatedly perform the same division process until the subsequences are trivially sorted (containing one or no element).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] An intuitive approach is the parallelization of those recursive calls.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] This algorithm is the trivial modification of the sequential version and does not parallelize well.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Therefore, its speedup is not very impressive.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] It has a span of $\Theta (n)$ , which is only an improvement of $\Theta (\log n)$ compared to the sequential version (see Introduction to Algorithms).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] This is mainly due to the sequential merge method, as it is the bottleneck of the parallel executions.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Better parallelism can be achieved by using a parallel merge algorithm.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Cormen et al. present a binary variant that merges two sorted sub-sequences into one sorted output sequence.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] In one of the sequences (the longer one if unequal length), the element of the middle index is selected.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Its position in the other sequence is determined in such a way that this sequence would remain sorted if this element were inserted at this position.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Thus, one knows how many other elements from both sequences are smaller and the position of the selected element in the output sequence can be calculated.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] For the partial sequences of the smaller and larger elements created in this way, the merge algorithm is again executed in parallel until the base case of the recursion is reached.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] The following pseudocode shows the modified parallel merge sort method using the parallel merge algorithm (adopted from Cormen et al.).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] For detailed information about the complexity of the parallel merge procedure, see Merge algorithm.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] This parallel merge algorithm reaches a parallelism of ${\textstyle \Theta \left({\frac {n}{(\log n)^{2}}}\right)}$ , which is much higher than the parallelism of the previous algorithm.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Such a sort can perform well in practice when combined with a fast stable sequential sort, such as insertion sort, and a fast sequential merge as a base case for merging small arrays.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] It seems arbitrary to restrict the merge sort algorithms to a binary merge method, since there are usually p > 2 processors available.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] A better approach may be to use a K-way merge method, a generalization of binary merge, in which k sorted sequences are merged.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] This merge variant is well suited to describe a sorting algorithm on a PRAM.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Given an unsorted sequence of n elements, the goal is to sort the sequence with p available processors.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] These elements are distributed equally among all processors and sorted locally using a sequential Sorting algorithm.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Hence, the sequence consists of sorted sequences $S_{1},...,S_{p}$ of length ${\textstyle \lceil {\frac {n}{p}}\rceil }$ .
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] For simplification let n be a multiple of p , so that ${\textstyle \left\vert S_{i}\right\vert ={\frac {n}{p}}}$ for $i=1,...,p$ .
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] These sequences will be used to perform a multisequence selection/splitter selection.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] For $j=1,...,p$ , the algorithm determines splitter elements $v_{j}$ with global rank ${\textstyle k=j{\frac {n}{p}}}$ .
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Then the corresponding positions of $v_{1},...,v_{p}$ in each sequence $S_{i}$ are determined with binary search and thus the $S_{i}$ are further partitioned into p subsequences $S_{i,1},...,S_{i,p}$ with ${\textstyle S_{i,j}:=\{x\in S_{i}|rank(v_{j-1})<rank(x)\leq rank(v_{j})\}}$ .
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Furthermore, the elements of $S_{1,i},...,S_{p,i}$ are assigned to processor i , means all elements between rank ${\textstyle (i-1){\frac {n}{p}}}$ and rank ${\textstyle i{\frac {n}{p}}}$ , which are distributed over all $S_{i}$ .
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Thus, each processor receives a sequence of sorted sequences.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] The fact that the rank k of the splitter elements $v_{i}$ was chosen globally, provides two important properties: On the one hand, k was chosen so that each processor can still operate on ${\textstyle n/p}$ elements after assignment.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] The algorithm is perfectly load-balanced.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] On the other hand, all elements on processor i are less than or equal to all elements on processor $i+1$ .
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Hence, each processor performs the *p*-way merge locally and thus obtains a sorted sequence from its sub-sequences.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Because of the second property, no further *p*-way-merge has to be performed, the results only have to be put together in the order of the processor number.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] In its simplest form, given p sorted sequences $S_{1},...,S_{p}$ distributed evenly on p processors and a rank k , the task is to find an element x with a global rank k in the union of the sequences.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Hence, this can be used to divide each $S_{i}$ in two parts at a splitter index $l_{i}$ , where the lower part contains only elements which are smaller than x , while the elements bigger than x are located in the upper part.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] The presented sequential algorithm returns the indices of the splits in each sequence, e.g. the indices $l_{i}$ in sequences $S_{i}$ such that $S_{i}[l_{i}]$ has a global rank less than k and $\mathrm {rank} \left(S_{i}[l_{i}+1]\right)\geq k$ .
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] For the complexity analysis the PRAM model is chosen.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] If the data is evenly distributed over all p , the p-fold execution of the *binarySearch* method has a running time of ${\mathcal {O}}\left(p\log \left(n/p\right)\right)$ .
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] The expected recursion depth is ${\mathcal {O}}\left(\log \left(\textstyle \sum _{i}|S_{i}|\right)\right)={\mathcal {O}}(\log(n))$ as in the ordinary Quickselect.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Thus the overall expected running time is ${\mathcal {O}}\left(p\log(n/p)\log(n)\right)$ .
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Applied on the parallel multiway merge sort, this algorithm has to be invoked in parallel such that all splitter elements of rank ${\textstyle i{\frac {n}{p}}}$ for $i=1,..,p$ are found simultaneously.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] These splitter elements can then be used to partition each sequence in p parts, with the same total running time of ${\mathcal {O}}\left(p\,\log(n/p)\log(n)\right)$ .
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Below, the complete pseudocode of the parallel multiway merge sort algorithm is given.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] We assume that there is a barrier synchronization before and after the multisequence selection such that every processor can determine the splitting elements and the sequence partition properly.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Firstly, each processor sorts the assigned $n/p$ elements locally using a sorting algorithm with complexity ${\mathcal {O}}\left(n/p\;\log(n/p)\right)$ .
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] After that, the splitter elements have to be calculated in time ${\mathcal {O}}\left(p\,\log(n/p)\log(n)\right)$ .
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Finally, each group of p splits have to be merged in parallel by each processor with a running time of ${\mathcal {O}}(\log(p)\;n/p)$ using a sequential p-way merge algorithm.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] The multiway merge sort algorithm is very scalable through its high parallelization capability, which allows the use of many processors.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] This makes the algorithm a viable candidate for sorting large amounts of data, such as those processed in computer clusters.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Also, since in such systems memory is usually not a limiting resource, the disadvantage of space complexity of merge sort is negligible.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] However, other factors become important in such systems, which are not taken into account when modelling on a PRAM.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Here, the following aspects need to be considered: Memory hierarchy, when the data does not fit into the processors cache, or the communication overhead of exchanging data between processors, which could become a bottleneck when the data can no longer be accessed via the shared memory.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Sanders et al. have presented in their paper a bulk synchronous parallel algorithm for multilevel multiway mergesort, which divides p processors into r groups of size $p'$ .
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Unlike single level multiway mergesort, these sequences are then partitioned into r parts and assigned to the appropriate processor groups.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] These steps are repeated recursively in those groups.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] This reduces communication and especially avoids problems with many small messages.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] The hierarchical structure of the underlying real network can be used to define the processor groups (e.g. racks, clusters,...).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Merge sort was one of the first sorting algorithms where optimal speed up was achieved, with Richard Cole using a clever subsampling algorithm to ensure *O*(1) merge.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Other sophisticated parallel sorting algorithms can achieve the same or better time bounds with a lower constant.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] For example, in 1991 David Powers described a parallelized quicksort (and a related radix sort) that can operate in *O*(log *n*) time on a CRCW parallel random-access machine (PRAM) with *n* processors by performing partitioning implicitly.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Although heapsort has the same time bounds as merge sort, it requires only Θ(1) auxiliary space instead of merge sort's Θ(*n*).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] On typical modern architectures, efficient quicksort implementations generally outperform merge sort for sorting RAM-based arrays.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Quicksorts are preferred when the data size to be sorted is lesser, since the space complexity for quicksort is O(log *n*), it helps in utilizing cache locality better than merge sort (with space complexity O(n)).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] On the other hand, merge sort is a stable sort and is more efficient at handling slow-to-access sequential media.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] As of Perl 5.8, merge sort is its default sorting algorithm (it was quicksort in previous versions of Perl).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] In Java, the Arrays.sort() methods use merge sort or a tuned quicksort depending on the datatypes and for implementation efficiency switch to insertion sort when fewer than seven array elements are being sorted.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] The Linux kernel uses merge sort for its linked lists.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/merge-sort] Timsort, a tuned hybrid of merge sort and insertion sort is used in variety of software platforms and languages including the Java and Android platforms and is used by Python since version 2.3; since version 3.11, Timsort's merge policy was updated to Powersort.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] In computer science, **comparator networks** are abstract devices built up of a fixed number of "wires", carrying values, and comparator modules that connect pairs of wires, swapping the values on the wires if they are not in a desired order.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] Such networks are typically designed to perform sorting on fixed numbers of values, in which case they are called **sorting networks**.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] Sorting networks differ from general comparison sorts in that they are not capable of handling arbitrarily large inputs, and in that their sequence of comparisons is set in advance, regardless of the outcome of previous comparisons.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] In order to sort a larger number of inputs, new sorting networks must be constructed.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] This independence of comparison sequences is useful for parallel execution and for implementation in hardware.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] Despite the simplicity of sorting nets, their theory is surprisingly deep and complex.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] Sorting networks were first studied circa 1954 by Armstrong, Nelson and O'Connor, who subsequently patented the idea.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] Sorting networks can be implemented either in hardware or in software.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] Donald Knuth describes how the comparators for binary integers can be implemented as simple, three-state electronic devices.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] Batcher, in 1968, suggested using them to construct switching networks for computer hardware, replacing both buses and the faster, but more expensive, crossbar switches.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] Since the 2000s, sorting nets (especially bitonic mergesort) are used by the GPGPU community for constructing sorting algorithms to run on graphics processing units.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] A sorting network consists of two types of items: comparators and wires.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] The wires are thought of as running from left to right, carrying values (one per wire) that traverse the network all at the same time.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] When a pair of values, traveling through a pair of wires, encounter a comparator, the comparator swaps the values if and only if the top wire's value is greater or equal to the bottom wire's value.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] In a formula, if the top wire carries x and the bottom wire carries y, then after hitting a comparator the wires carry $x'=\min(x,y)$ and $y'=\max(x,y)$ , respectively, so the pair of values is sorted.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] A network of wires and comparators that will correctly sort all possible inputs into ascending order is called a sorting network or Kruskal hub.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] By reflecting the network, it is also possible to sort all inputs into descending order.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] The full operation of a simple sorting network is shown below.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] It is evident why this sorting network will correctly sort the inputs; note that the first four comparators will "sink" the largest value to the bottom and "float" the smallest value to the top.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] The final comparator sorts out the middle two wires.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] The efficiency of a sorting network can be measured by its total size, meaning the number of comparators in the network, or by its *depth*, defined (informally) as the largest number of comparators that any input value can encounter on its way through the network.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] We can easily construct a network of any size recursively using the principles of insertion and selection.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] Assuming we have a sorting network of size *n*, we can construct a network of size *n* + 1 by "inserting" an additional number into the already sorted subnet (using the principle underlying insertion sort).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] We can also accomplish the same thing by first "selecting" the lowest value from the inputs and then sort the remaining values recursively (using the principle underlying bubble sort).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] The structure of these two sorting networks are very similar.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] A construction of the two different variants, which collapses together comparators that can be performed simultaneously shows that, in fact, they are identical.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] The insertion network (or equivalently, bubble network) has a depth of 2*n* - 3, where *n* is the number of values.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] This is better than the *O*(*n* log *n*) time needed by random-access machines, but it turns out that there are much more efficient sorting networks with a depth of just *O*(log2 *n*), as described below.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] While it is easy to prove the validity of some sorting networks (like the insertion/bubble sorter), it is not always so easy.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] There are *n*! permutations of numbers in an n-wire network, and to test all of them would take a significant amount of time, especially when n is large.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] The number of test cases can be reduced significantly, to 2*n*, using the so-called zero-one principle.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] While still exponential, this is smaller than *n*! for all *n* ≥ 4, and the difference grows quite quickly with increasing n.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] The zero-one principle states that, if a sorting network can correctly sort all 2*n* sequences of zeros and ones, then it is also valid for arbitrary ordered inputs.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] This not only drastically cuts down on the number of tests needed to ascertain the validity of a network, it is of great use in creating many constructions of sorting networks as well.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] By induction on the depth of the network, this result can be extended to a lemma stating that if the network transforms the sequence *a*1, ..., *a**n* into *b*1, ..., *b**n*, it will transform *f*(*a*1), ..., *f*(*a**n*) into *f*(*b*1), ..., *f*(*b**n*).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] Suppose that some input *a*1, ..., *a**n* contains two items *ai* < *aj*, and the network incorrectly swaps these in the output.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] This function is monotonic, so we have the zero-one principle as the contrapositive.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] Various algorithms exist to construct sorting networks of depth *O*(log2 *n*) (hence size *O*(*n* log2 *n*)) such as Batcher odd–even mergesort, bitonic sort, Shell sort, and the Pairwise sorting network.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] These networks are often used in practice.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] It is also possible to construct networks of depth *O*(log *n*) (hence size *O*(*n* log *n*)) using a construction called the *AKS network*, after its discoverers Ajtai, Komlós, and Szemerédi.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] While an important theoretical discovery, the AKS network has very limited practical application because of the large linear constant hidden by the Big-O notation.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] These are partly due to a construction of an expander graph.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] A simplified version of the AKS network was described by Paterson in 1990, who noted that "the constants obtained for the depth bound still prevent the construction being of practical value".
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] A more recent construction called the *zig-zag sorting network* of size *O*(*n* log *n*) was discovered by Goodrich in 2014.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] While its size is much smaller than that of AKS networks, its depth *O*(*n* log *n*) makes it unsuitable for a parallel implementation.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] For small, fixed numbers of inputs n, *optimal* sorting networks can be constructed, with either minimal depth (for maximally parallel execution) or minimal size (number of comparators).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] These networks can be used to increase the performance of larger sorting networks resulting from the recursive constructions of, e.g., Batcher, by halting the recursion early and inserting optimal nets as base cases.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] For larger networks neither the optimal depth nor the optimal size are currently known.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] For one to twelve inputs, minimal (i.e. size-optimal) sorting networks are known, and for higher values, lower bounds on their sizes *S*(*n*) can be derived inductively using a lemma due to Van Voorhis (p.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] The first ten optimal networks have been known since 1969, with the first eight again being known as optimal since the work of Floyd and Knuth, but optimality of the cases *n* = 9 and *n* = 10 took until 2014 to be resolved.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] The optimality of the smallest known sorting networks for *n* = 11 and *n* = 12 was resolved in 2020.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] Some work in designing optimal sorting network has been done using genetic algorithms: D.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] Knuth mentions that the *smallest* known sorting network for *n* = 13 was found by Hugues Juillé in 1995 "by simulating an evolutionary process of genetic breeding" (p.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] 226), and that the *minimum depth* sorting networks for *n* = 9 and *n* = 11 were found by Loren Schwiebert in 2001 "using genetic methods" (p.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/sorting-network] Unless P=NP, the problem of testing whether a candidate network is a sorting network is likely to remain difficult for networks of large sizes, due to the problem being co-NP-complete.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] In computer science, a **sorting algorithm** is an algorithm that puts elements of a list into an order.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] The most frequently used orders are numerical order and lexicographical order, and either ascending order or descending order.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Efficient sorting is important for optimizing the efficiency of other algorithms (such as search and merge algorithms) that require input data to be in sorted lists.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Sorting is also often useful for canonicalizing data and for producing human-readable output.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] The output is a permutation (a reordering, yet retaining all of the original elements) of the input.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Although some algorithms are designed for sequential access, the highest-performing algorithms assume data is stored in a data structure which allows random access.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] From the beginning of computing, the sorting problem has attracted a great deal of research, perhaps due to the complexity of solving it efficiently despite its simple, familiar statement.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Among the authors of early sorting algorithms around 1951 was Betty Holberton, who worked on ENIAC and UNIVAC.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Bubble sort was analyzed as early as 1956.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Asymptotically optimal algorithms have been known since the mid-20th century – new algorithms are still being invented, with the widely used Timsort dating to 2002, and the library sort being first published in 2006.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Comparison sorting algorithms have a fundamental requirement of $n\log {n}-1.4427n+O(\log {n})$ comparisons.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Algorithms not based on comparisons, such as counting sort, can have better performance.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Sorting small arrays optimally (in the fewest comparisons and swaps) or fast (i.e. taking into account machine-specific details) is still an open research problem, with solutions only known for very small arrays (fewer than 20 elements).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Similarly optimal (by various definitions) sorting on a parallel machine is an open research topic.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Stability is important to preserve order over multiple sorts on the same data set.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] For example, say that student records consisting of name and class section are sorted dynamically, first by name, then by class section.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] If a stable sorting algorithm is used in both cases, the sort-by-class-section operation will not change the name order; with an unstable sort, it could be that sorting by section shuffles the name order, resulting in a nonalphabetical list of students.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] More formally, the data being sorted can be represented as a record or tuple of values, and the part of the data that is used for sorting is called the *key*.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] In the card example, cards are represented as a record (rank, suit), and the key is the rank.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] A sorting algorithm is stable if whenever there are two records R and S with the same key, and R appears before S in the original list, then R will always appear before S in the sorted list.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] When equal elements are indistinguishable, such as with integers, or more generally, any data where the entire element is the key, stability is not an issue.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Stability is also not an issue if all keys are different.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Unstable sorting algorithms can be specially implemented to be stable.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] One way of doing this is to artificially extend the key comparison so that comparisons between two objects with otherwise equal keys are decided using the order of the entries in the original input list as a tie-breaker.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Remembering this order, however, may require additional time and space.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] One application for stable sorting algorithms is sorting a list using a primary and secondary key.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] For example, suppose we wish to sort a hand of cards such that the suits are in the order clubs (♣), diamonds (♦), hearts (♥), spades (♠), and within each suit, the cards are sorted by rank.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Within each suit, the stable sort preserves the ordering by rank that was already done.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] This idea can be extended to any number of keys and is utilised by radix sort.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] The same effect can be achieved with an unstable sort by using a lexicographic key comparison, which, e.g., compares first by suit, and then compares by rank if the suits are the same.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] This analysis assumes that the length of each key is constant and that all comparisons, swaps and other operations can proceed in constant time.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Mathematical analysis demonstrates a comparison sort cannot perform better than *O*(*n* log *n*) on average.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Performs a combination of Quicksort, Heapsort, and Insertion sort.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] in-place stable merge algorithm, such as rotate merge or symmerge.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] An optimization of Selection Sort, which uses a tournament tree to select the min/max.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] comparisons when the data is already sorted or reverse sorted.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] An adaptive branchless stable introsort.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] An in-place, but unstable variant of Fluxsort.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Complexity is influenced by the gap sequence used.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Tight bounds for the average and worst case remain open problems.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Can be run on parallel processors easily.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Noted for its simplicity and small number of element moves.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] In-place with theoretically optimal number of writes.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] The following table describes integer sorting algorithms and other sorting algorithms that are not comparison sorts.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] These algorithms are not limited to *Ω*(*n* log *n*) unless meet unit-cost random-access machine model as described below.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Samplesort can be used to parallelize any of the non-comparison sorts, by efficiently distributing data into several buckets and then passing down sorting to several processors, with no need to merge as buckets are already sorted between each other.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Some algorithms are slow compared to those discussed above, such as the bogosort with unbounded run time and the stooge sort which has *O*(*n*2.7) run time.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] These sorts are usually described for educational purposes to demonstrate how the run time of algorithms is estimated.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] The following table describes some sorting algorithms that are impractical for real-life use in traditional software contexts due to extremely poor performance or specialized hardware requirements.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] While there are a large number of sorting algorithms, in practical implementations a few algorithms predominate.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Insertion sort is widely used for small data sets, while for large data sets an asymptotically efficient sort is used, primarily heapsort, merge sort, or quicksort.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Efficient implementations generally use a hybrid algorithm, combining an asymptotically efficient algorithm for the overall sort with insertion sort for small lists at the bottom of a recursion.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Highly tuned implementations use more sophisticated variants, such as Timsort (merge sort, insertion sort, and additional logic), used in Android, Java, and Python, and introsort (quicksort and heapsort), used (in variant forms) in some C++ sort implementations and in .NET.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] For more restricted data, such as numbers in a fixed interval, distribution sorts such as counting sort or radix sort are widely used.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Bubble sort and variants are rarely used in practice, but are commonly found in teaching and theoretical discussions.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] When physically sorting objects (such as alphabetizing papers, tests or books) people intuitively generally use insertion sorts for small sets.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] For larger sets, people often first bucket, such as by initial letter, and multiple bucketing allows practical sorting of very large sets.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Often space is relatively cheap, such as by spreading objects out on the floor or over a large area, but operations are expensive, particularly moving an object a large distance – locality of reference is important.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Merge sorts are also practical for physical objects, particularly as two hands can be used, one for each list to merge, while other algorithms, such as heapsort or quicksort, are poorly suited for human use.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Other algorithms, such as library sort, a variant of insertion sort that leaves spaces, are also practical for physical use.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Two of the simplest sorts are insertion sort and selection sort, both of which are efficient on small data, due to low overhead, but not efficient on large data.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Insertion sort is generally faster than selection sort in practice, due to fewer comparisons and good performance on almost-sorted data, and thus is preferred in practice, but selection sort uses fewer writes, and thus is used when write performance is a limiting factor.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] The algorithm finds the minimum value, swaps it with the value in the first position, and repeats these steps for the remainder of the list.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] It does no more than *n* swaps and thus is useful where swapping is very expensive.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Practical general sorting algorithms are almost always based on an algorithm with average time complexity (and generally worst-case complexity) O(*n* log *n*), of which the most common are heapsort, merge sort, and quicksort.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Each has advantages and drawbacks, with the most significant being that simple implementation of merge sort uses O(*n*) additional space, and simple implementation of quicksort has O(*n*2) worst-case complexity.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] These problems can be solved or ameliorated at the cost of a more complex algorithm.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] While these algorithms are asymptotically efficient on random data, for practical efficiency on real-world data various modifications are used.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] First, the overhead of these algorithms becomes significant on smaller data, so often a hybrid algorithm is used, commonly switching to insertion sort once the data is small enough.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Second, the algorithms often perform poorly on already sorted data or almost sorted data – these are common in real-world data and can be sorted in O(*n*) time by appropriate algorithms.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Finally, they may also be unstable, and stability is often a desirable property in a sort.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Thus more sophisticated algorithms are often employed, such as Timsort (based on merge sort) or introsort (based on quicksort, falling back to heapsort).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Merge sort has seen a relatively recent surge in popularity for practical implementations, due to its use in the sophisticated algorithm Timsort, which is used for the standard sort routine in the programming languages Python and Java (as of JDK7).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Merge sort itself is the standard routine in Perl, among others, and has been used in Java at least since 2000 in JDK1.3.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] The important caveat about quicksort is that its worst-case performance is O(*n*2); while this is rare, in naive implementations (choosing the first or last element as pivot) this occurs for sorted data, which is a common case.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] The most complex issue in quicksort is thus choosing a good pivot element, as consistently poor choices of pivots can result in drastically slower O(*n*2) performance, but good choice of pivots yields O(*n* log *n*) performance, which is asymptotically optimal.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] For example, if at each step the median is chosen as the pivot then the algorithm works in O(*n* log *n*).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Finding the median, such as by the median of medians selection algorithm is however an O(*n*) operation on unsorted lists and therefore exacts significant overhead with sorting.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] In practice choosing a random pivot almost certainly yields O(*n* log *n*) performance.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] If a guarantee of O(*n* log *n*) performance is important, there is a simple modification to achieve that.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] The idea, due to Musser, is to set a limit on the maximum depth of recursion.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] If that limit is exceeded, then sorting is continued using the heapsort algorithm.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Musser proposed that the limit should be $1+2\lfloor \log _{2}(n)\rfloor$ , which is approximately twice the maximum recursion depth one would expect on average with a randomly ordered array.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] The worst-case time complexity of Shellsort is an open problem and depends on the gap sequence used, with known complexities ranging from *O*(*n*2) to *O*(*n*4/3) and Θ(*n* log2 *n*).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] This, combined with the fact that Shellsort is in-place, only needs a relatively small amount of code, and does not require use of the call stack, makes it is useful in situations where memory is at a premium, such as in embedded systems and operating system kernels.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Bubble sort, and variants such as the Comb sort and cocktail sort, are simple, highly inefficient sorting algorithms.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] They are frequently seen in introductory texts due to ease of analysis, but they are rarely used in practice.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Counting sort is applicable when each input is known to belong to a particular set, *S*, of possibilities.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] The algorithm runs in O(|*S*| + *n*) time and O(|*S*|) memory where *n* is the length of the input.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] It works by creating an integer array of size |*S*| and using the *i*th bin to count the occurrences of the *i*th member of *S* in the input.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Each input is then counted by incrementing the value of its corresponding bin.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Afterward, the counting array is looped through to arrange all of the inputs in order.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] This sorting algorithm often cannot be used because *S* needs to be reasonably small for the algorithm to be efficient, but it is extremely fast and demonstrates great asymptotic behavior as *n* increases.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] It also can be modified to provide stable behavior.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Bucket sort is a divide-and-conquer sorting algorithm that generalizes counting sort by partitioning an array into a finite number of buckets.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Each bucket is then sorted individually, either using a different sorting algorithm or by recursively applying the bucket sorting algorithm.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] A bucket sort works best when the elements of the data set are evenly distributed across all buckets.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] In *Algorithms and Data Structures* Niklaus Wirth gives a comparison of the running time of several of the popular algorithms on the Lilith computer.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] In this scenario, the total number of comparisons becomes (relatively) less important, and the number of times sections of memory must be copied or swapped to and from the disk can dominate the performance characteristics of an algorithm.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Thus, the number of passes and the localization of comparisons can be more important than the raw number of comparisons, since comparisons of nearby elements to one another happen at system bus speed (or, with caching, even at CPU speed), which, compared to disk speed, is virtually instantaneous.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] In that scenario, another algorithm may be preferable even if it requires more total comparisons.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] One way to work around this problem, which works well when complex records (such as in a relational database) are being sorted by a relatively small key field, is to create an index into the array and then sort the index, rather than the entire array.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] This procedure is sometimes called "tag sort".
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Another technique for overcoming the memory-size problem is using external sorting, for example, one of the ways is to combine two algorithms in a way that takes advantage of the strength of each to improve overall performance.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] For instance, the array might be subdivided into chunks of a size that will fit in RAM, the contents of each chunk sorted using an efficient algorithm (such as quicksort), and the results merged using a *k*-way merge similar to that used in merge sort.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] This is faster than performing either merge sort or quicksort over the entire list.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] For sorting very large sets of data that vastly exceed system memory, even the index may need to be sorted using an algorithm or combination of algorithms designed to perform reasonably with virtual memory, i.e., to reduce the amount of swapping required.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Related problems include approximate sorting (sorting a sequence to within a certain amount of the correct order), partial sorting (sorting only the *k* smallest elements of a list, or finding the *k* smallest elements, but unordered) and selection (computing the *k*th smallest element).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] These can be solved inefficiently by a total sort, but more efficient algorithms exist, often derived by generalizing a sorting algorithm.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] The most notable example is quickselect, which is related to quicksort.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Conversely, some sorting algorithms can be derived by repeated application of a selection algorithm; quicksort and quickselect can be seen as the same pivoting move, differing only in whether one recurses on both sides (quicksort, divide-and-conquer) or one side (quickselect, decrease-and-conquer).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] A kind of opposite of a sorting algorithm is a shuffling algorithm.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] These are fundamentally different because they require a source of random numbers.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Shuffling can also be implemented by a sorting algorithm, namely by a random sort: assigning a random number to each element of the list and then sorting based on the random numbers.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] This is generally not done in practice, however, and there is a well-known simple and efficient algorithm for shuffling: the Fisher–Yates shuffle.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Sorting algorithms are ineffective for finding an order in many situations.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] Usually, when elements have no reliable comparison function (crowdsourced preferences like voting systems), comparisons are very costly (sports), or when it would be impossible to pairwise compare all elements for all criteria (search engines).
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] In these cases, the problem is usually referred to as *ranking* and the goal is to find the "best" result for some criteria according to probabilities inferred from comparisons or rankings.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] A common example is in chess, where players are ranked with the Elo rating system, and rankings are determined by a tournament system instead of a sorting algorithm.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] There are sorting algorithms for a "noisy" (potentially incorrect) comparator and sorting algorithms for a pair of "fast and dirty" (i.e.
[src:merge-sort-algorithm/stable-sort] This can be useful when the full comparison function is costly.
